---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="World Time Zones: Why Clocks Show Different Times" description="How time zones work, why they exist, and how to convert between them. GMT/UTC, daylight saving, and the Date Line." keywords="time zones explained, world time zones, GMT UTC, time zone conversion, international date line, daylight saving time, time difference">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Time</span>
      </nav>
      <BlogCrossLinks title="World Time Zones: Why Clocks Show Different Times" />
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">July 18, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>When it is noon in London, it is 7 AM in New York and 9 PM in Tokyo. Time zones let the world keep a sensible relationship between clock time and the position of the sun — but the system is surprisingly complex.</p>

      <h2>Why Time Zones Exist</h2>
      <p>Before time zones, every town set its own clock by the sun. When railways connected distant cities in the 1800s, this became chaotic — a train timetable was impossible when every station had a different "noon." In 1884, the International Meridian Conference divided the world into 24 zones, each 15 degrees of longitude wide.</p>

      <h2>UTC: The Reference Point</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">UTC (Coordinated Universal Time) = the global reference</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">GMT (Greenwich Mean Time) is effectively the same as UTC+0</p>
      </div>
      <p>All time zones are expressed as offsets from UTC: UTC+5:30 (India), UTC-5 (US Eastern), UTC+9 (Japan), etc.</p>

      <h2>Major Time Zones</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>UTC-8:</strong> US Pacific (Los Angeles, Seattle)</li>
        <li><strong>UTC-5:</strong> US Eastern (New York, Miami)</li>
        <li><strong>UTC+0:</strong> UK, Portugal, Iceland (GMT)</li>
        <li><strong>UTC+1:</strong> Central Europe (Paris, Berlin, Madrid)</li>
        <li><strong>UTC+5:30:</strong> India (all of India uses one zone)</li>
        <li><strong>UTC+8:</strong> China, Singapore, Western Australia</li>
        <li><strong>UTC+9:</strong> Japan, Korea</li>
        <li><strong>UTC+10:</strong> Eastern Australia (Sydney)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Daylight Saving Time (DST)</h2>
      <p>Many countries shift clocks forward 1 hour in summer (spring forward) and back in winter (fall back). This creates confusion because:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Not all countries observe DST</li>
        <li>Countries switch on different dates</li>
        <li>Southern hemisphere countries are offset by 6 months</li>
        <li>For a few weeks each year, the time difference between two cities may be unusual</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Unusual Time Zones</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>India:</strong> UTC+5:30 (half-hour offset)</li>
        <li><strong>Nepal:</strong> UTC+5:45 (45-minute offset)</li>
        <li><strong>Chatham Islands (NZ):</strong> UTC+12:45</li>
        <li><strong>China:</strong> Uses only one time zone despite spanning 5 geographic zones</li>
        <li><strong>Australia:</strong> Has a UTC+9:30 zone (South Australia)</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/tools/clock" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open World Clock →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/tools/clock" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Tool →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
